  "doc_id": "27434",
  "text": "Work stealing is a technique for achieving dynamic load balancing in high-performance computing. In an OpenCL context, work stealing involves each work-group owning a task queue, and idle threads popping tasks from another workgroup's queue should their own queue become empty. The ability to steal work is valuable when it is impractical to distribute tasks evenly among work-groups at compile-time -either because of a non-uniform computational cost per task that depends on input data, or because new tasks can be created dynamically at run-time [CITATION_1] .",
